# 11- Adding code or Code block

To print a string use `print("Codanics")`

`print("Hello Baba G")`

> For block of code:

```
x = 5 + 6
y = 3 - 2
z = x + y
print(z)
```

> If you write python the block of code will work in python.
> This code will show color according to Python language syntax.

```python
x = 5 + 6
y = 3 - 2
z = x + y
print(z)
```

> Similarly,
> This code will show color according to R language syntax.

```R
x = 5 + 6
y = 3 - 2
z = x + y
print(z)
```


# 12- Adding tables

> Add colons to align the tables
> Colons to left for left align, Right for right align and on both sides for middle align


| Species | petal_length | sepal_length |
|---------:|:--------------:|:--------------|
| viginica| 18.2 | 19.2 |
| setosa | 15.2 | 17.2 |
| virginica | 16.2 | 18.2 |
| viginica| 18.2 | 19.2 |
| setosa | 15.2 | 17.2 |
| virginica | 16.2 | 18.2 |



# 13- Installing Extensions

> The work we have done till now, to make it more easier like words we have some extensions.
> For Example:

**Bold** (Ctrl+B)

**Italic** (Ctrl+I)

**~~Strikethrough~~**

***Italic and Bold***(Ctrl+I B)

[Link](https://youtu.be/qJqAXjz-Rh4?si=Ab5oNY7muNEJCftc)

![Image](abdu.JPG) (Ctrl + L)

Column A | Column B | Column C
---------|----------|---------
 A1 | B1 | C1
 A2 | B2 | C2
 A3 | B3 | C3

Column A | Column B | Column C
---------|----------|---------
 A1 | B1 | C1
 A2 | B2 | C2
 A3 | B3 | C3

> And so on these are the shortcuts of the extensions we installed that makes easier for us to create a markdown sheet. These are:
* Markdown All in One
* Markdown Pdf
* Markdownlint
* Markdown Shortcut
